result.execSummary:
All charges against Ashley A Zastrow in this case have been dismissed. These charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Ashley A Zastrow is presumed innocent.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
02:02 PM Defendant Ashley A Zastrow in court with attorney Greg Venturini.  Matthew Steven McElroy appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Roger Sir appears by Zoom, is sworn as a witness and questioned by Attorney McElroy. He is a law enforcement officer for Lincoln County. On 2/18/22, he conducted a mirandarized interview with THG regarding the shooting of a woman who died. THG stated that the firearm was purchased at Ace Hardware in Wisconsin Rapids with the assistance of the defendant. Two firearms were purchased for for $379 and $275.  He stated that the guns were going to be exchanged for drugs. The firearms were purchased on 1/15/22. He stated one of those firearms were recovered at the scene of the shooting. He reviewed surveillance video from Ace Hardware on 1/15/22 where he observed defendant and THG looking at guns and defendant filled out the paperwork and paid for the firearms and ammunition. Based on background check, THG is a convicted felon and not allowed to possess a firearm. The witness identifies the defendant in the courtroom.  He states what defendant told him about purchasing the firearms. Attorney McElroy asks Court take judicial notice of Marathon County case 19CF644, a felony conviction for THG. Court takes judicial notice. Attorney Venturini cross-examines witness. Attorney McElroy redirects.
Attorney McElroy makes statement.
Attorney Venturini makes statement. He asks that case be dismissed.
Court grants motion for dismissal without prejudice.
